=== Modern Period === With modernization, the state assumed final legal authority over religious institutions, and internal temple laws lost legal standing. Early Meiji-era policies, including {{ill|Haibutsu kishaku|ja|廃仏毀釈|1=Haibutsu kishaku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haibutsu kishaku|13=User:Immanuelle/Haibutsu kishaku|qq=}} and state-sanctioned Shinto reforms, significantly impacted Buddhist and Shinto institutions. By 1871, temple lands were seized, and Shinto priests became government-appointed officials. However, by 1884, the state relinquished direct control over religious appointments, and religious organizations were granted limited autonomy. The {{ill|Constitution of the Empire of Japan|ja|大日本帝国憲法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Constitution of the Empire of Japan|qq=}} acknowledged restricted freedom of religion, leading Buddhist sects to advocate for legal recognition of temple properties. In 1939, the {{ill|Religious Organizations Law|ja|宗教団体法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Religious Organizations Law|qq=}} was enacted, granting legal corporate status to temples while increasing state control. After World War II, religious freedom was reaffirmed under the {{ill|Constitution of Japan|ja|日本国憲法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Constitution of Japan|qq=}}, leading to the enactment of the {{ill|Religious Corporations Law|ja|宗教法人法|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Religious Corporations Law|qq=}} in 1951, which remains the foundation of religious administration in Japan today. == References == * Kazuyoshi Sunagawa, "Temple Law" (Social Science Encyclopedia Vol. 9, Kashima Research Institute, 1975) * Nobumichi Inaba, "Temple Law" (Historical Studies Encyclopedia Vol. 9, Kōbundō, 2002) * Yoshihide Kiyota, "Jisha Law" (National History Encyclopedia Vol. 7, Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 1986)
}}
