{{wikidata link|Q11458107|ja|寺院法}} [[Category: occurred only about a century later, making it a valuable source for understanding the early state’s view of Buddhism. After Prince Shōtoku’s death, in the 32nd year of Empress Suiko’s reign (624 AD), a system for appointing high-Ranking Buddhist officials was established based on the institutions of the Chinese Southern Dynasties. {{ill|Jianzhen|en|Jianzhen|WD=Q714061|lt=Ganjin|1=Jianzhen}} [[Category:Buddhism in Japan]] [[Category:History of Buddhism in Japan]] [[Category:Japanese Religious Law]] [[Category:Legal history of Japan]] [[Category:Wikidata no short description]]
